# ADS-B Live Flight Tracker                                                                          
                                                                                                       
  Real-time ADS-B flight visualization piped from a FlightRadar24 Raspberry Pi feeder to a live web    
  map.                                                                                                 
                                                                                                       
  A Raspberry Pi running FlightRadar24 OS decodes ADS-B signals from aircraft overhead using an SDR    
  antenna and `dump1090-mutability`, which writes live aircraft data to a local JSON file. A bash
  forwarder script on the Pi reads that file every 3 seconds and POSTs it to a Node.js backend hosted
  on Railway. The backend broadcasts updates to connected browsers via WebSocket, and the frontend
  plots aircraft on a Leaflet.js map in real time with callsign labels, popups showing altitude, speed,
   heading, squawk, and signal strength.

  ## Stack
  - **Pi-side:** bash + systemd service, reads from `dump1090-mutability`
  - **Backend:** Node.js, Express, ws — hosted on Railway
  - **Frontend:** Leaflet.js, plain HTML/JS — served by the backend

  ---

  ## Setting up for yourself

  ### Prerequisites
  - Raspberry Pi running FlightRadar24 OS with an SDR antenna attached
  - `dump1090-mutability` running with the `--write-json` flag (standard on FR24 OS)
  - A Railway account for hosting the backend
  - A GitHub repo for the backend code

  ### 1. Verify dump1090 is writing data
  SSH into your Pi and confirm the data file exists and is populated:

  ```bash
  ls /run/dump1090-mutability/
  cat /run/dump1090-mutability/aircraft.json
  ```

  You should see a JSON object with an aircraft array. An empty array just means no planes are
  currently in range.

  Check that dump1090-mutability is running:

  ps aux | grep dump1090

  ### 2. Set up the Pi forwarder
  Create the script:

  ```bash
  sudo mkdir -p /opt/adsb-forwarder
  sudo nano /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh
  ```

  Paste this in, filling in your Railway URL and API key:

  ```bash
  #!/bin/bash
  AIRCRAFT_FILE="/run/dump1090-mutability/aircraft.json"
  CLOUD_ENDPOINT="https://your-backend.railway.app/api/aircraft"
  API_KEY="your-key"
  TMPFILE=$(mktemp)

  while true; do
      if [ -f "$AIRCRAFT_FILE" ]; then
          cp "$AIRCRAFT_FILE" "$TMPFILE"
          curl --http1.1 -s -X POST "$CLOUD_ENDPOINT" \
              -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
              -H "X-API-Key: $API_KEY" \
              --data "@$TMPFILE" \
              > /dev/null
      fi
      sleep 3
  done
  ```

  ▎ Note: The script copies to a temp file and uses --data @file instead of passing the JSON as a shell
   variable — this avoids bash misinterpreting JSON characters as redirects. --http1.1 is required to
  avoid HTTP/2 stream errors on the Pi's version of curl.

  Make it executable:

  `sudo chmod +x /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh`

  Register it as a systemd service so it runs on boot:

  `sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/adsb-forwarder.service`

  [Unit]
  Description=ADS-B Data Forwarder
  After=network.target

  [Service]
  ExecStart=/bin/bash /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh
  Restart=always
  User=pi

  [Install]
  WantedBy=multi-user.target

  Enable and start it:

  `sudo systemctl enable adsb-forwarder`
  `sudo systemctl start adsb-forwarder`
  `sudo systemctl status adsb-forwarder`

  ### 3. Deploy the backend to Railway
  Push the project to a GitHub repo, then in Railway:

  1. New project → Deploy from GitHub repo → connect your repo
  2. Go to the service → Variables tab and add:
  API_KEY = your-key
  3. Railway auto-detects Node.js and deploys. Copy your Railway URL.

  The backend keeps WebSocket connections alive through Railway's proxy by sending a ping every 25
  seconds.

  ### 4. Update the forwarder with your Railway URL

  Edit the script on the Pi:

  `sudo nano /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh`

  Update CLOUD_ENDPOINT and API_KEY, then restart:

  `sudo systemctl restart adsb-forwarder`

  ### 5. Update the frontend

  In public/index.html, set your Railway URL and map center coordinates:

  ```bash
  const ws = new WebSocket(`wss://your-backend.railway.app`);
  const map = L.map('map').setView([YOUR_LAT, YOUR_LON], 9);
  ```

  ### 6. Test the pipeline

  From the Pi, send a test aircraft to verify the full pipeline end to end (must be a single unbroken
  line):

  ```bash
  curl --http1.1 -X POST https://your-backend.railway.app/api/aircraft -H "Content-Type:
  application/json" -H "X-API-Key: your-key" -d '{"aircraft":[{"hex":"test01","lat":42.787,"lon"
  :-71.332,"altitude":20000,"speed":350,"track":280,"squawk":"1200"}]}'
  ```

  You should get `{"ok":true,"count":1}` back and see a plane appear on the map.

  ---
  If you need to update the API key, change in both places:
  - Railway → Variables tab → API_KEY
  - Pi → /opt/adsb-forwarder/forwarder.sh → API_KEY=

  After changing it in either place, restart the forwarder:

  `sudo systemctl restart adsb-forwarder`

  ---
  Notes

  - aircraft.json is updated by dump1090 roughly every second; the forwarder POSTs every 3 seconds
  - Not all aircraft broadcast a callsign — the ICAO hex code is used as a fallback label
  - dump978-fr24 also runs on FR24 OS for UAT (978 MHz) used by smaller GA aircraft in the US — this
  project only uses 1090 MHz ADS-B data from dump1090-mutability
  - The history_*.json files in /run/dump1090-mutability/ are a rolling 120-entry position history
  buffer — not used here but useful if you want to draw flight trails
  - Railway's free trial gives $5 of credit; after that the Hobby plan is $5/month